            <li>You need <b>offline access</b> or a <b>native mobile app</b></li>
            <li><b>70&ndash;80% design match</b> is acceptable for an internal tool</li>
            <li>You prefer the <b>Power Apps ecosystem</b> (Teams embed, managed environment)</li>
            <li>The Kanban pipeline can use dropdown status changes instead of drag-drop</li>
        </ul>
    </td>
    <td>
        <ul>
            <li>You want the <b>exact same interface</b> as the current React app</li>
            <li>You want to <b>finish faster</b> by reusing existing code (2&ndash;3 days)</li>
            <li><b>External stakeholders or clients</b> need access</li>
            <li>The <b>Kanban drag-drop</b> and <b>quadrant scatter plot</b> must work as-is</li>
            <li>Your team has basic <b>HTML/CSS/JS skills</b> (or uses AI to generate)</li>
            <li>You can cover the <b>Power Pages license cost</b></li>
        </ul>
    </td>
</tr>
</table>

<!-- ==================== SECTION 8 ==================== -->
<h2>8. Final Recommendation</h2>

<div class="callout-green">
<h3>Best result in least time &rarr; Method B (Power Pages)</h3>
<p>You already have a complete, working React application. Method B converts it to Power Pages in <b>2&ndash;3 days</b> with <b>~95&ndash;100% design fidelity</b>. AI handles the React-to-vanilla-JS conversion in minutes per component. The scoring logic, CSS, charts, Kanban board, and rating widget all carry over. The only real coding is swapping localStorage for ~10 lines of Dataverse Web API calls per service file. If you can cover the Power Pages license, this is the fastest and highest-fidelity path.</p>

<h3>Lowest ongoing cost &rarr; Method A (Canvas App)</h3>
<p>If the Power Pages license is a concern, or you want business users to maintain the app without developer support, Method A is the safer long-term choice. It takes 3&ndash;5 days, the design won't be pixel-perfect, but it's a solid internal tool with zero extra licensing cost.</p>

<h3>Hybrid: Start with B, add A for mobile</h3>
<p>Since both methods share the same Dataverse tables, you can deploy Power Pages for the full-fidelity web experience, then build a lightweight Canvas App on the same data for mobile/Teams access later.</p>
